1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:04,900
Just as a theme park manager might delegate tasks to staff members throughout the park,

2

00:00:04,900  -->  00:00:10,340
Python allows you to delegate error handling to the parts of the code best suited for it.

3

00:00:10,340  -->  00:00:16,080
This is very useful when multiple functions in a program can encounter similar errors,

4

00:00:16,080  -->  00:00:19,260
and we want a higher-level function to take care of them.

5

00:00:19,260  -->  00:00:26,355
In a sense, we ask Python to escalate up to make an executive decision about what to do.

6

00:00:26,355  -->  00:00:30,910
Let's talk about delegating responsibility for handling exceptions.

7

00:00:30,910  -->  00:00:35,910
Imagine that each attraction at the park might break down.

8

00:00:35,910  -->  00:00:39,490
But we want a central team to handle repairs.

9

00:00:39,490  -->  00:00:42,170
We'll create a function to simulate this where

10

00:00:42,170  -->  00:00:46,850
the attractions pass on the error to a repair team.

11

00:00:46,850  -->  00:00:49,370
First, we'll write a function,

12

00:00:49,370  -->  00:00:52,995
and we'll say def ride_operation.

13

00:00:52,995  -->  00:00:56,810
We'll then pass in a ride as a parameter.

14

00:00:56,810  -->  00:00:58,630
We'll say if ride,

15

00:00:58,630  -->  00:01:03,685
not in roller coaster or ferris wheel,

16

00:01:03,685  -->  00:01:05,460
this will be our list.

17

00:01:05,460  -->  00:01:08,560
Then we will raise a value error,

18

00:01:08,560  -->  00:01:11,040
and that will return an F string,

19

00:01:11,040  -->  00:01:19,820
and it'll say ride the input into the function as an argument is not a valid ride.

20

00:01:19,820  -->  00:01:23,865
Once it's checked against the list that we define there,

21

00:01:23,865  -->  00:01:26,560
we'll then close out our value error,

22

00:01:26,560  -->  00:01:30,120
and that rounds out our ride operation function.

23

00:01:30,120  -->  00:01:33,780
Now what we'll do is we'll define a managed park function,

24

00:01:33,780  -->  00:01:36,215
so we'll say def manage_park,

25

00:01:36,215  -->  00:01:38,960
also passing in ride as a parameter.

26

00:01:38,960  -->  00:01:43,330
We'll say try and we'll say ride_operation,

27

00:01:43,330  -->  00:01:47,280
which is the same function that we have up here.

28

00:01:47,280  -->  00:01:49,780
We pass in ride similarly,

29

00:01:49,780  -->  00:01:52,795
and then we'll print an F statement.

30

00:01:52,795  -->  00:01:59,770
F string, and we'll say the ride is running smoothly.

31

00:01:59,770  -->  00:02:01,515
Close out our print statement.

32

00:02:01,515  -->  00:02:05,605
Then we'll have an except case branch,

33

00:02:05,605  -->  00:02:08,675
where we'll say ValueError as E,

34

00:02:08,675  -->  00:02:10,870
and we'll say print F,

35

00:02:10,870  -->  00:02:13,230
and we'll say maintenance team.

36

00:02:13,230  -->  00:02:17,500
We have an issue ride,

37

00:02:17,500  -->  00:02:20,540
and that's in squiggly brackets,

38

00:02:20,540  -->  00:02:22,380
and then we'll pass in the error,

39

00:02:22,380  -->  00:02:24,875
also in squiggly brackets.

40

00:02:24,875  -->  00:02:29,840
We'll close the F string with the end quote.

41

00:02:29,840  -->  00:02:32,510
Then we'll close out the print statement like that.

42

00:02:32,510  -->  00:02:35,960
Now, if we were to run this,

43

00:02:35,960  -->  00:02:38,500
where we say manage_park water slide,

44

00:02:38,500  -->  00:02:42,435
notice how we're going to invoke this function.

45

00:02:42,435  -->  00:02:44,440
Once we pass and ride,

46

00:02:44,440  -->  00:02:48,310
this is the argument here because we have a parameter here.

47

00:02:48,310  -->  00:02:53,600
This is going to call the ride operation function, which is here.

48

00:02:53,600  -->  00:02:56,090
Then that passes in that same input.

49

00:02:56,090  -->  00:03:03,100
This is going to return information that we can then use in the manage park function.

50

00:03:03,100  -->  00:03:06,210
If we were to pass this into manage park,

51

00:03:06,210  -->  00:03:08,850
can you guess what the output of this is going to be?

52

00:03:08,850  -->  00:03:12,390
When we run this, we're going to see maintenance team.

53

00:03:12,390  -->  00:03:14,690
We have an issue with the water slide error.

54

00:03:14,690  -->  00:03:17,110
Water slide is not a valid ride,

55

00:03:17,110  -->  00:03:20,430
which makes sense because it's not in this list.

56

00:03:20,430  -->  00:03:24,050
But since roller coaster and ferris wheel are both valid rides,

57

00:03:24,050  -->  00:03:26,410
if we were to run something like this,

58

00:03:26,410  -->  00:03:29,610
where we say manage ride roller coaster,

59

00:03:29,610  -->  00:03:32,970
we will see the roller coaster is running smoothly.

60

00:03:32,970  -->  00:03:40,485
Here, the ride operation function checks if the ride is valid in this list here.

61

00:03:40,485  -->  00:03:43,775
If not, it raises a value error,

62

00:03:43,775  -->  00:03:49,070
this exception is then caught by the manage park function in here,

63

00:03:49,070  -->  00:03:52,870
which handles it by alerting the maintenance team because this will

64

00:03:52,870  -->  00:03:57,915
cause the except ValueError as E branch to be invoked.

65

00:03:57,915  -->  00:04:02,670
This method lets us centralize our error handling across our Python code,

66

00:04:02,670  -->  00:04:07,170
making the code cleaner and more manageable. Great work.
